First, I checked that the T4 GPU in Google Colab was working properly because training on CPU would take more than 10 hours. Then, I uploaded my leaf dataset from Google Drive to Colab so I could access it easily. After that, I set all the training parameters like batch size, learning rate, and number of epochs to make the training efficient and get good results.
I had around 400 photos per species, which was not enough for deep learning. So, I increased my dataset by applying data augmentation techniques like flipping, rotating, blurring, and cropping. After doing this, my dataset expanded to 4000 total images (400 per species × 10 species). This helped my model learn better and reduced overfitting.
In my model, the encoder takes a leaf photo and converts it into 512 numerical features that represent important patterns. Then, SimCLR compresses these 512 features into 128 features so they can be compared easily. The NT-Xent Loss helped train the model by making sure that images of the same leaf are similar, while different leaf images are kept apart.
I trained my model for 100 epochs without using any labels. What I did was — I took one leaf photo and created two different augmented versions of it, like one flipped and one rotated. Then I trained the model so that these two versions are treated as similar in the embedding space, while all other different leaf images are pushed apart. In this way, my model gradually learned the important features that define each type of leaf on its own.
After my model learned the leaf features, I added a small classifier on top and started giving it labels like Neem, Mango, etc. Since the encoder had already understood the patterns, it learned classification very quickly.
My training strategy was simple — for the first 10 epochs, I kept the encoder frozen and trained only the classifier. After that, I unfroze the entire model and trained everything together. This fine-tuning process took around 5 minutes.
Then I tested my model on completely unseen leaf images to check its performance. I measured test accuracy to see how many leaves were correctly identified, and also calculated precision, recall, and F1-score for each species. I also used a confusion matrix to understand which leaf types the model was getting confused between.
Finally, to prove that self-supervised learning actually helped, I performed transfer learning experiments. In one experiment, I used my pretrained encoder, and in another, I trained a model from scratch. This comparison clearly showed that my pretrained model performed better and learned faster.
